<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-481-549  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 481 549.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 8 1990 v7 n40 p12(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Unisys unveils integrated systems architecture. (IntegratedInformation Environment architecture)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Musich, Paula.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Unisys Corp announces its Integrated Information Environmentarchitecture, an open systems strategy that follows the lead ofother major systems vendors in creating multivendor distributedsystems.andP;  Integrated Information Environment is designed as aplatform for creating applications that run across heterogeneousnetworks and migrating applications to multiple hardwareplatforms.andP;  It defines five types of services: connectivity,distributed systems, information management, applicationmanagement, and information and systems management.andP;  The companyhas enhanced several of its products to support the newarchitecture and made major revisions in its mainframe operatingsystems.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Unisys Corp. (planning).andO;Ticker:    UIS.andO;Topic:     Computer systems integrationStrategic PlanningProduct DevelopmentStandardizationOpen Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Paula MusichandM;NEW YORK -- Unisys Corp. last week became one of the last major systemsvendors to announce its architecture for creating integrated, multivendorinformation systems, but one of the first to build its architecture aroundexisting products and standards.andM;Unisys' newly defined Integrated Information Environment architecture drawson its existing Open Systems Interconnect (OSI) products and CASE/fourth-generation language (4GL) development tools.andP;  The architecture isbuilt on a base of more than 150 existing products put in place since thefirm was formed in 1986 from the merger of mainframe vendors Sperry Corp. andBurroughs Corp.andM;It is designed as a platform for creating distributed applications andmigrating existing applications to distributed computing environments of PCs,minicomputers and mainframes.andM;At a press conference here, Unisys officials also announced several new orenhanced products that implement pieces of the architecture, including majorrevisions to the firm's mainframe operating systems, new OSI-based messaging,file-transfer and lower-layer protocol support for its A Series mainframes,and enhanced X.400 messaging support for its 1100/2200 mainframes.andM;Unisys also announced versions of its Mapper and Ally 4GL products for ATandamp;T3B2 and NCR Tower Unix-based minicomputers, along with a Mapperimplementation for OS/2.andM;Users and analysts briefed on the architecture applauded it.andM;&quot;The most significant thing about the architecture is that they're workingtoward being able to provide products that conform to open standards,&quot; saidJ.C.andP;  Ruch, director of technical services and communications at CreightonUniversity in Omaha, Neb.andM;Also key to the framework is its focus on multiplatform development tools,according to Kevin O'Neill, vice president of network research and consultingfor market researcher Business Research Group in Newton, Mass.andM;&quot;They're trying to address how to migrate to a truly distributedenvironment,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;They have an aggressive set of tools for the Unisysinstalled base, and they're trying to address non-Unisys COBOL applicationsas well.&quot;andM;The architecture defines five types of services that will be supported:systems connectivity, distributed systems, information management,application and information and systems management.andP;  Three platform typesthat will be supported are information hubs based on its mainframes, serversbased primarily on its Unix systems, and workstations or work groups based onDOS, OS/2, CTOS/ Open and Unix operating systems.andO;</TEXT></DOC>